    <td width="613" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top"><font color="#808080" size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica"><strong><a name="author's bio">author bio</a> </strong></font><p><img src="muglouiseerdrich.gif" alt="Louise Erdrich" align="left" hspace="4" vspace="4" WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="151"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2" color="#000080">Louise Erdrich was born in
    Little Falls, Minnesota, but she grew up mostly in Wahpeton, North Dakota, where her
    parents taught at Bureau of Indian Affairs schools. She is an enrolled member of the
    Turtle Mountain Chippewa tribe of North Dakota. Her fiction reflects aspects of her mixed
    heritage: German through her father, and French and Ojibwa through her mother. Her first
    novel, <em>Love Medicine,</em> won the National Book Critics Circle Award. Set on a North
    Dakota reservation, it focuses on the relations between three Chippewa families. These
    same memorably eccentric characters appear in later novels as well where we also find the
    addition of Euro-American townspeople of the region. In all, she has written nine novels,
    most recently <em>The Last Report on the Miracles at Little No Horse </em>(2002), which
    was a National Book Award finalist. A new novel, <em>The Master Butchers Singing Club, </em>is
    due out in February 2003. She has also won numerous awards for her short fiction, much of
    which has been anthologized, and for her children's fiction (<em>The BirchBark House,</em>
    1999, was also a National Book Award finalist). Her work has been translated into fourteen
    languages. She lives in Minnesota with her children, who help her run a small independent
    bookstore called The BirchBark. <br>
